Investigating Management Practices Across Countries and Industries

Author: Alex Lucas

This project is a look into the management practices of schools, hospitals, and companies across many countries. Comparing the scores between a variety of different groups provided great insight into trends of management quality and where improvements can be made. This project is guided by Doing Economics Empirical Project 6 where the data is provided and questions are asked to provoke analytical thought. The two data files for this project can be accessed here and here.

6.1¶

1a. Briefly describe how the interviews with managers were conducted, and explain some methods the researchers used to improve the reliability and validity of their data.

The interviews with managers were conducted by MBA students who had business experience. They asked the managers open questions (rather than yes or no questions) on their management practices. Based on their answers, the interviewers gave them a score from 1 to 5, 1 being bad management practice and 5 being very good management practice. The interviewers did not tell the managers anything about the scoring system and the interviewers were not given any information about the companies beforehand. These measures along with a few others were put in place to remove bias in the results.

1b. Do you think that these are the best criteria for assessing management practices? What (if any) important aspects of management are not included in this assessment?

It was interesting to read about how different management practices can enhance productivity much more or much less depending on the environment of a company or even the culture of a company. One thing I thought of is that some employees could respond negatively to monitoring so more monitoring is not necessarily always better, which is a potential issue with the current methodology. Also, I think another factor that could be added is whether management is cultivating a positive or friendly environment. It can definitely enhance productivity if coworkers are friendly with each other and have a positive attitude towards their work.

#This code creates an array of numbers from 1 to 5 in increments of .2 to be referenced later as the bins.
range_of_scores = np.arange(1,5.2,.2)

#This code creates the frequency table for the US management scores with each column:
# "Ranges", "Frequency" and "Percentage of Firms"
US_scores = manu_data.loc[manu_data['country'] == 'United States', 'management']
frequency_US = US_scores.value_counts(bins=range_of_scores, sort=False)
percentage_of_firms_US = frequency_US/sum(frequency_US) * 100

US_frequency_table = pd.DataFrame(frequency_US)
US_frequency_table.insert(1,'% of Firms',percentage_of_firms_US)
US_frequency_table.rename(columns={"management": "Frequency"},inplace=True)
US_frequency_table.reset_index(inplace=True)
US_frequency_table.rename(columns={"index": "Ranges"},inplace=True)

display(HTML(US_frequency_table.to_html()))

3c) Describe any visual similarities and differences between the distributions of your chosen countries and that of the US.

The US distribution seems to be centered around a higher score than all the other distributions. It seems like the US has a higher percentage of firms on the right side of the distribution than all three countries, while all 3 countries have a higher percentage of firms on the left side of the distribution than the US. This indicates that there is likely a higher overall average for the US. In addition, all three countries tend to have larger spreads than the US because they tend to have some very good scores and some poor scores, while the US is more consistent in having relatively good scores.

5c) Using your average criteria scores from Question 5(a), suggest some explanations for the observed rankings in either hospitals or schools.

It makes sense that the United States is the highest scoring country from a pure management perspective in hospitals and schools because the U.S. has many policies of universal standardization. For example, in schools, common core laws require certain curricula to be taught and standardized tests to be taken throughout the country to make sure students are on track. This definitely increases the scores in every category for the US because students are monitored, given targets, and incentives throughout their schooling career.

In addition, a possible explanation for France being the lowest scoring country is that according to peoplesdispatch.org, the French healthcare system has been underfunded and neglected by the government. In France, healthcare is funded almost completely through tax revenue and managed by the government, so it’s possible that the government is worse at managing hospitals than private companies would be. This is interesting however, because the UK has a universal health care system and ranks much higher than France, so there may be other factors at play.

https://peoplesdispatch.org/2020/06/17/french-health-workers-hit-the-streets-demand-government-to-save-public-health-system/

1b) Margin of error for each country: Z-score can be used because all sample sizes are greater than 100.

United States: 1.96(.642848/sqrt(1225)) = .0360
Australia: 1.96(.577252/sqrt(392)) = .0572
Japan: 1.96(.614942/sqrt(176)) = .0909
Portugal: 1.96(.626236/sqrt(247)) = 0.0781

#This code creates a bar plot for mean management scores and includes 
#error bars to represent the 95% confidence interval.

labels = ['United States','Australia','Japan','Portugal']
x_pos = np.arange(len(labels))

#These are the mean scores for every country.
US_mean = country_score_summary['mean'].iloc[0]
Aus_mean = country_score_summary['mean'].iloc[1]
Japan_mean = country_score_summary['mean'].iloc[2]
Port_mean = country_score_summary['mean'].iloc[3]
means = [US_mean, Aus_mean, Japan_mean,Port_mean]

1c) This is a bar chart with the mean management scores and the error bars represent the 95% confidence interval.

In [21]:
#This is the size of the sample "n", or the number of firms, for each country.
US_n = (manu_data['country']=='United States').sum()
Aus_n = (manu_data['country']=='Australia').sum()
Japan_n = (manu_data['country']=='Japan').sum()
Port_n = (manu_data['country']=='Portugal').sum()

#This is the error calculated for each country using the margin of error formula.
US_error = 1.96*(country_score_summary['std'].iloc[0]/math.sqrt(US_n))
Aus_error = 1.96*(country_score_summary['std'].iloc[1]/math.sqrt(Aus_n))
Japan_error = 1.96*(country_score_summary['std'].iloc[2]/math.sqrt(Japan_n))
Port_error = 1.96*(country_score_summary['std'].iloc[3]/math.sqrt(Port_n))
error = [US_error, Aus_error, Japan_error, Port_error]

#This is the code setting up the bar plot.
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.bar(x_pos, means, yerr = error, align='center', alpha=0.5, ecolor='black',capsize=10)
ax.set_xticks([0,1,2,3])
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.set_ylabel('Mean Management Score')
ax.set_xlabel('Country')
ax.set_title('Mean Management Scores with 95% Confidence')
ax.yaxis.grid(True)

1d) Use the width of the confidence intervals to describe how precisely each mean was estimated. For the US, the width of the confidence interval is narrow which shows the mean is estimated precisely. Australia’s is wider than the U.S., but narrower than Japan and Portugal’s, so Australia’s mean is estimated the second most precisely. Japan and Portugal have similarly wider margins of error than the US and Australia meaning their means are estimated less precisely.

1e) Using your chart from Question 1(c) and the rule of thumb, what can you say about the differences between the US management score, and the scores of other countries? How would your results change if you use a different specified probability (for example, 99%)?

The mean management score for the United States is estimated much more precisely than the other countries because it is a significantly larger sample size which allows the mean to be estimated better. If a 99% confidence interval was used, the margin of error would be greater for each country, but they would all be scaled the same so countries would not change in ranking of margin of error size.

US_mean_hs = management_score_summary_hs['mean'].iloc[6]

#This is the size of the sample "n", or the number of hospitals and schools, for each country.
Canada_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='Canada').sum()
France_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='France').sum()
Germany_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='Germany').sum()
Italy_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='Italy').sum()
Sweden_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='Sweden').sum()
UK_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='UK').sum()
US_n_hs = (hospital_school_data['country']=='US').sum()

#This is the error calculated for each country using the margin of error formula.
Canada_error_hs = 1.96*(management_score_summary_hs['std'].iloc[0]/math.sqrt(Canada_n_hs))
France_error_hs = 1.96*(management_score_summary_hs['std'].iloc[1]/math.sqrt(France_n_hs))

Are there any countries for which you can be confident that management practices are either better, or worse, on average than in the US? Explain your answer. You can be almost completely certain that Canada, France, Germany, and Italy, have a lower true population mean score than the US because the upper bound of their confidence intervals are still lower than the lower bound of the US confidence interval. However, there is still a small chance that the true US mean score is lower than its confidence interval and a small chance that each of the mentioned countries could have a true mean score higher than their confidence interval.

3) Look at the width of your confidence intervals and the corresponding standard deviation and number of observations for each one. Explain whether or not the relationship between them is what you would expect.

It makes sense that the US and UK in hospitals and schools have narrow confidence intervals because they have smaller standard deviations and much larger sample sizes than the other countries. It also makes sense that Japan in manufacturing has a very wide confidence interval because it has a larger standard deviation and a smaller sample size. The smaller the standard deviation and larger the sample size, the smaller the confidence interval is going to be. And the larger the standard deviation and smaller the sample size, the larger the confidence interval is going to be.

This is the bar plot showing the mean management scores for public and private schools with 95% confidence.

Describe the differences between public and private firms within countries and compare management scores for the same firm type across countries. (For example, is one type of firm generally better managed than the other? Are there similar patterns for hospitals and schools?

It seems that private firms are generally managed better than public firms within their respective firm types. However, private firms, especially in schools, tended to have wider confidence intervals because the sample size was generally smaller, which means their mean estimates are less precise. It does not look like one firm type is generally better managed than the other. They appear to have a similar distribution centered around a score of about 2.75. It’s interesting to see that Sweden was only second to the US in private healthcare, and ranked at the top in private schooling, however in the overall hospital and schooling ranking, Sweden was below the US and UK. This is likely because Sweden’s less good public hospitals and schools bring the average down. It’s also interesting that the US has very good scores for hospitals, but gets beat out by many other countries in schools. This shows that the US was ranked highly in the overall ranking because of its hospitals rather than its schools.

3. For each of the following variables, explain how it could affect management practices, and then explain how management practices could affect it: education level of managers (percentage with a college degree) number of competitors firm size (number of employees).

Increasing education level of managers can definitely improve management practices because managers with formal training in business will have a better idea of proven organization methods such as monitoring and setting targets and incentives than those that are not educated.

Increasing the number of competitors could mean the market attracts more talented managers which would increase the management score. However, an increasing number of competitors could also mean that there are many new firms entering the market with poor management, which could decrease management scores. A market with less competitors could have high management scores if the market is controlled by a few large corporations with good management.

Higher firm sizes could mean that the companies are able to pay higher salaries and attract better management talent, which would increase management score. However, large firms are also more difficult to manage because there are more people and moving parts, so this could also decrease management scores.

4. Briefly describe the idea behind a randomized field experiment, and explain, with reference to the results of the experiment in India, whether we can use it to determine the direction of causation between management practice and firm performance.

A randomized field experiment is an experiment where a group of companies is selected randomly to be given a treatment, and their results are compared to a randomly selected control group that is not given any treatment. This is a way to show that the treatment can have a strong correlation towards a certain effect on management practices. Generally, more research is needed to determine whether there is a causal effect however.

Figure 12 in the paper shows productivity in treatment and control firms over time, with 95% confidence intervals. Use the information in the chart to describe the effect of the treatment on firm productivity.

The treatment seems to have a positive correlation with increased productivity over time because the treatment group increases at a higher rate than the control plans and the difference between the two grows larger and larger. It seems that the effect of the treatment had smaller effects in the short-term, but greater effects in the long term because the productivity for the treatment group is increasing at an increasing rate as time goes on.
